{
  "text": "The altered functions of the pgACC in migraine have been reported in previous fMRI studies. Increased activation was found in migraine patients to trigeminonociceptive stimulation compared to controls also in the rostral part of the ACC [CITATION_1] . Emphasizing the importance of our results, previous fMRI studies using trigeminal heat stimulation to induce acute pain in migraine patients, found increased brain activation in the pgACC with almost identical MNI coordinates as reported here [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . One of these studies showed that this enhanced activation to noxious heat reduced after a 60 day successful treatment with external trigeminal neurostimulation [CITATION_4] . The authors suggested that the pgACC could be involved in the antinociceptive effect of the antimigraine treatment [CITATION_5] . Our results are in line with these results as we found that this region is more active in migraine patients after a small increase of 5-HT levels compared to pain-free healthy controls. These observations together suggest that increased sensitivity of the ACC in migraine patients might be related to altered serotonergic control of the incoming excitatory signals.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "45037173",
    "[CITATION_2]": "14809068",
